SENATE RESOLUTION 366
By Walley
A RESOLUTION to commend Teria Tibbs for exemplary service
as a legislative intern.
WHEREAS, each legislative session, this legislative body is pleased to recognize certain
persons who have committed themselves, through their adroit service, to the betterment of the
legislative process; and
WHEREAS, Teria Tibbs is one such individual, who has distinguished herself in her role
as a legislative intern for Senator Page Walley; and
WHEREAS, Ms. Tibbs's work, her exceptionally personable demeanor, and her
professionalism have resulted in innumerable benefits for the legislators she assisted, the
constituents of Senate District 26, and the General Assembly as a whole; and
WHEREAS, Teria Tibbs was born in Nashville and is a graduate of St. Cecilia Academy;
she is the grandchild of Brenda and Marcus Tibbs, youngest and only daughter of Kesha Tibbs,
niece of Teric Tibbs, and sister of Rashean Tibbs; and
WHEREAS, Ms. Tibbs is devoted to her family, with whom she enjoys spending time,
especially her baby cousin, Isaiah Tibbs; and
WHEREAS, a student at Lipscomb University, where she is highly regarded by her
peers, Ms. Tibbs has achieved academic success while pursuing a degree in political science;
her many achievements include being on the Honor Roll and the Provost's List; receiving the
Lipscomb Memorial Award, the Community Vision Award, and the Bison Achievement Award;
placing third in the Duet Acting National and second in the Acting State/Regional; and receiving
the medal for Best Performance in Advanced Speech and Drama; and
SR0366
017041
- 1 -

WHEREAS, Teria Tibbs is a compassionate volunteer who served the Second Harvest
Food Bank of Middle Tennessee in 2021 by organizing and managing nutritious resources to be
distributed to those in need within her community; and
WHEREAS, during her collegiate career, Ms. Tibbs has participated in numerous
extracurricular activities, including serving as a witness and attorney for the Mock Trial team;
serving as a leading actress and Vice President of the Theater Guild; and serving as event
planner, Social Media Coordinator, and Treasurer of the Black Student Association; she has
found a passion for learning languages and discovering new cultures; and
WHEREAS, upon graduating from Lipscomb University, Teria Tibbs aspires to become
an attorney and serve her community, with a quote by Malcolm X always standing firm in her
heart, "We want to get behind leaders who will fight for us … leaders who are not afraid to
demand freedom, justice, and equality"; and
WHEREAS, eager to familiarize herself with the characteristics and complexities of
Tennessee State government and to further her studies, Ms. Tibbs brought her many abilities
and singular expertise to Capitol Hill for the 2026 session of the One Hundred Fourteenth
General Assembly; and
WHEREAS, Teria Tibbs has performed her many duties with extraordinary insight and
rare decorum; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE ONE HUNDRED FOURTEENTH
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, that we hereby commend Teria
Tibbs for outstanding service as a legislative intern for Senator Page Walley and extend to her
our best wishes for every future success.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy.
